  - Positives vs my preferences: It delivers intimate close‑mic lead vocals, tight three/four‑part harmonies, and concise 2–4‑minute melody‑first hooks — those align with my love of emotive, singer‑forward leads, tight harmonies and compact songcraft. The subtle remaster trims tape hiss while preserving warm analogue sonics and transient attack, which matches my dislike of excessive hiss and my desire for preserved dynamics. The description explicitly calls the mixes layered and singer‑forward and says they reveal detail on repeat listens, which is also a strong match.
  - Potential negatives vs my dislikes: it’s mono‑friendly and explicitly intimate/close‑mic. While I accept “wide stereo or focused mono” when the vocal remains emotive and forward, my stated preference for strong stereo imaging and clear instrument separation is better served by stereo mixes; mono reduces stereo imaging and instrument separation (even if it focuses the vocal). Also, this is an album (not a curated hits collection) and some of the Beatles’ arrangements can be relatively intimate in a way that risks softness; although this particular remaster is described as punchy, the mono/intimate presentation is a closer call versus my preference for the punch and separation typical of AOR hits packages.
Why I chose Tight AOR greatest‑hits and rejected Mono‑friendly Beatles For Sale
- Primary alignment with core priorities: The AOR greatest‑hits collection more closely matches the core cluster of my highest‑priority preferences: a well‑curated hits collection, controlled AOR/pop‑rock arrangements, punchy remastering that preserves transients and attack, and strong stereo imaging with clear instrument separation. Those attributes are repeatedly emphasized in my introduction (I prize curated hits collections, AOR/pop‑rock control, stereo imaging, and remasters that keep punch), and the Tight AOR greatest‑hits description hits those notes directly.
